---
All database access in WatchAgent (app/) must go through repository classes.

REPOSITORIES:
  ReadingRepository  (app/repositories/reading_repo.py)
    .insert(reading: RawReading)         → WeatherReading | None
    .get_recent(city, limit)             → list[WeatherReading]
    .get_all(city, limit)                → list[WeatherReading]

  EventRepository  (app/repositories/event_repo.py)
    .insert(event_data: dict)            → WeatherEvent
    .get_all(city, limit)                → list[WeatherEvent]

RULES:
- Routes (app/api/routes/) MUST use a repository instance. They MUST NOT call
  db.query() or db.execute() directly. Import the repository, instantiate it
  with the injected Session, and call its methods.

  CORRECT:
    repo = ReadingRepository(db)
    rows = repo.get_recent(city, limit=limit)

  WRONG (will be flagged):
    db.query(WeatherReading).filter(...).all()

- Services (app/services/) MUST use repositories for all persistence.
  The only exception is ReadingRepository calling db.query() internally —
  that is the repository implementation, not a violation.

- When a new query is needed (e.g., a new API filter, a count endpoint),
  add a method to the relevant repository. Do NOT write the query inline
  in the route or service that needs it.

- Repositories receive a Session from the caller. They do NOT create their
  own SessionLocal(). Session lifetime is the caller's responsibility.
  Exception: _run_cross_city_detection in poller.py opens its own session
  because it runs after per-city sessions have been closed — this is
  intentional and documented.

- Repositories commit inside their own methods (current design). Do NOT
  add extra db.commit() calls in routes or services.

WHY:
  Keeping all db.query() calls inside repositories means a new engineer
  (or Cursor) adding an endpoint cannot accidentally bypass the unique-
  constraint check, the ordering convention (timestamp.desc()), or the
  session rollback pattern. It also keeps routes thin and testable without
  touching ORM internals.
